BT /F2 9.50 Tf 0.040 0.340 0.780 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 754.00 Tm (SAY \(read aloud\)) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 738.00 Tm (Let's open with a question. Your application has an ArrayList with a thousand students added) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 723.00 Tm (through the day. Then the server restarts - a deploy, a crash, a power blip. Where is your data) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 708.00 Tm (now? Look at the two panels. On the left, while the program runs, the list has five students -) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 693.00 Tm (everything is fine. On the right, after a restart, the list is empty. The objects lived in RAM, and RAM) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 678.00 Tm (is cleared, so they are gone. This is the single idea the whole session rests on: in-memory data) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 663.00 Tm (lives only as long as the JVM lives. A database persists data beyond the process - it survives) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 648.00 Tm (restarts, crashes, and redeploys. JDBC is the bridge from your Java objects to that durable store.) Tj ET
