BT /F2 9.50 Tf 0.040 0.340 0.780 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 481.00 Tm (SAY \(read aloud\)) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 465.00 Tm (So what exactly is JDBC? The crucial insight is that JDBC is mostly a set of interfaces - it lives in) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 450.00 Tm (the java dot s-q-l package, and it is not a framework, just a set of contracts that say what) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 435.00 Tm (operations exist. Card two: the database vendor provides the actual implementation, shipped as a) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 420.00 Tm (JAR file - that JAR is called the driver. One driver per database. Card three: every modern) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 405.00 Tm (database framework - JPA, Hibernate, Spring Data - sits on top of JDBC and generates these calls) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 390.00 Tm (for you. Why interfaces? Because your code talks to interfaces, it stays the same whether the) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 375.00 Tm (database underneath is MySQL, Oracle, PostgreSQL, or Derby. You swap the driver JAR and the) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 360.00 Tm (connection URL, and your logic is untouched.) Tj ET
