BT /F2 9.50 Tf 0.040 0.340 0.780 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 754.00 Tm (SAY \(read aloud\)) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 738.00 Tm (Here is how the pieces fit, top to bottom. At the top is your Java application - your code. Below it,) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 723.00 Tm (the JDBC API, the java dot s-q-l interfaces like Connection, PreparedStatement, and ResultSet.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 708.00 Tm (Below that sits DriverManager. Think of it as a matchmaker: you hand it a connection URL, and it) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 693.00 Tm (finds and loads the right driver. Next is the JDBC driver itself - the vendor's JAR, the concrete) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 678.00 Tm (implementation that knows how to speak one specific database's protocol. And at the bottom, the) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 663.00 Tm (database - MySQL, Derby, H2, whatever. The key thing: your code only ever touches the top two) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 648.00 Tm (layers. Everything below is handled for you once you have the driver on the classpath.) Tj ET
0.040 0.520 1.000 rg 58.00 633.00 3.00 127.00 re f
BT /F2 14.50 Tf 0.100 0.100 0.120 rg 1 0 0 1 58.00 617.00 Tm (Slide 6 - The four driver types) Tj ET
0.820 0.820 0.860 rg 58.00 600.00 496.00 1.20 re f
