BT /F1 10.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 570.00 Tm (A four-row table: Type 1 JDBC-ODBC bridge \(removed\), Type 2 Native API \(rare\), Type 3 Network protocol) Tj ET
BT /F1 10.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 556.50 Tm (\(legacy\), Type 4 Thin pure-Java \(industry standard\).) Tj ET
0.720 0.720 0.760 rg 58.00 543.00 3.00 49.00 re f
BT /F2 9.50 Tf 0.040 0.340 0.780 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 533.00 Tm (SAY \(read aloud\)) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 517.00 Tm (A little history, because interviewers ask and legacy code exists. JDBC drivers come in four types.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 502.00 Tm (Type 1, the JDBC-ODBC bridge, translated calls to ODBC - it was removed back in Java 8. Type) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 487.00 Tm (2, the Native API driver, used the database's own C or C-plus-plus libraries and needed a local) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 472.00 Tm (install - rare today. Type 3, the Network protocol driver, routed calls through a middleware server -) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 457.00 Tm (you see it in some legacy enterprise systems. And Type 4, the thin or pure-Java driver - a single) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 442.00 Tm (Java JAR that talks directly to the database's wire protocol. This is the industry standard.) Tj ET
0.040 0.520 1.000 rg 58.00 427.00 3.00 112.00 re f
